# api — deployment & packaging

How `@max/api` is built into a container and run in the cloud (Railway, but the
image stays portable). Embeddings go to Voyage over HTTP — there is no in-process
model, so the image carries no model weights or native ML addons.

## Build context is the repo root

- This is a pnpm workspace. The lockfile, `pnpm-workspace.yaml`, and the
  `@max/sandbox` package live ABOVE `packages/api`, so the Docker build context
  MUST be the repo root:
  `docker build -f packages/api/Dockerfile -t max-api .`
- `pnpm install --frozen-lockfile` validates the lockfile against EVERY workspace
  importer. Copy ALL `packages/*/package.json` in the build stage (even
  kb-tool/widget/shared) or the frozen install fails. Keep them out of the
  runtime image — they're build-stage only (see `.dockerignore`).

## Compiled JS resolution (exports map)

- `@max/sandbox`'s `exports` point at `./src/*.ts` so `tsx` can run sources in
  dev. Plain `node` CANNOT load `.ts`, so any `node`-run artifact (the image,
  `pnpm start`) needs those specifiers to resolve to compiled JS.
- The Dockerfile rewrites the DEPLOYED sandbox `exports` (`./src/X.ts` →
  `./dist/X.js`) — image-only. Do not "fix" this by pointing the repo exports at
  `dist`; that breaks `tsx` dev. If you make it permanent, use conditional
  exports so dev keeps resolving to source.
- Each shippable package sets `"files": ["dist"]` so `pnpm deploy` ships compiled
  output. Without it, deploy honors `.gitignore` (which ignores `dist/`) and
  ships nothing runnable.

## Migrations path in-container (common breakage)

- The migrator reads `${config.projectRoot}/db/migrations/*.sql` at boot
  (`RUN_MIGRATIONS_ON_BOOT=true`). `config.projectRoot` is
  `resolve(dir(import.meta.url), "../../..")` from the COMPILED sandbox config.
- GOTCHA: `pnpm deploy` puts the real sandbox in pnpm's virtual store
  (`node_modules/.pnpm/@max+sandbox@<hash>/node_modules/@max/sandbox`), and Node
  resolves the symlink to that real path. So `projectRoot` lands inside that
  hashed `.pnpm` dir, NOT `<app>/node_modules`. The hash is not stable, so the
  Dockerfile computes the exact path the app will use (realpath of the sandbox
  `dist` + `../../..`) and copies the `.sql` there — never hardcode the `.pnpm`
  path. If you change the runtime layout, re-derive this the same way.

## Runtime invariants

- Bind `0.0.0.0` (set explicitly in `index.ts`). A localhost/127.0.0.1 bind is
  unreachable inside a container and breaks health checks/routing.
- Port comes from `PORT` (default 8000). `HEALTHCHECK` hits `GET /health`.
- Secrets are runtime env only — never baked into the image or committed:
  `DATABASE_URL`, `VOYAGE_API_KEY`, `PORTKEY_API_KEY` (+ optional Portkey keys),
  `ADMIN_TOKEN`, `ALLOWED_ORIGINS`, `DATABASE_SSL`, `RUN_MIGRATIONS_ON_BOOT`.
- The image must NOT contain: TS sources, dev deps, `.env`, other workspace
  packages, sandbox CLI scripts, sample data, or model weights.

## CORS

- `ALLOWED_ORIGINS` is a comma-separated allow-list parsed in `config.ts`. An
  empty/unset value blocks ALL cross-origin requests (no allow-all fallback);
  `app.ts` logs a startup WARNING in that case. Set it to the widget origin(s).

## Populating the knowledge base (`scripts/bulkUpload.ts`)

- After a deploy the cloud DB is empty. `packages/api/scripts/bulkUpload.ts`
  (`pnpm --filter @max/api bulk-upload`) is the operator tool that fills it: it
  reads a folder of `.md` files and POSTs each, SEQUENTIALLY, to the deployed
  `POST /admin/documents`. It is a pure HTTP client — it does NOT import
  chunking/embedding logic (that runs server-side via `ingestDocument`).
- It MIRRORS the admin-documents contract in `packages/api/src/routes/admin.ts`
  (request body `{ source, content }`, Bearer auth, and the
  `indexed`/`skipped`/`empty`/error responses). If you change that route's
  request/response shape, status codes, or auth, UPDATE the script to match
  (it imports `IngestOutcome` type-only from `@max/sandbox/ingest` to stay
  aligned with the success shape).
- It lives in `scripts/` (outside `src/`) on purpose: it's run with `tsx`, is
  excluded from `tsc` build/typecheck, and must never ship in the image (see the
  runtime-invariants list — no CLI scripts in the image).
- `source` is the bare filename, matching the sandbox `ingest` CLI, so the
  server-side content-hash idempotency aligns: re-running is safe and unchanged
  docs return `skipped`. The script exits non-zero if any file errored.
